Pods Restarting Frequently

Your application is deployed.

Pods are running.

But after a few minutes, you notice:

❌ Restart Count Increasing

❌ Application Instability

❌ Unexpected Service Disruptions

Frequent pod restarts are often symptoms of deeper issues within the application or infrastructure.

Recently, I encountered a production workload where pods were restarting repeatedly, causing intermittent application outages.

🔍 My troubleshooting approach:

✅ Checked pod restart count

✅ Reviewed pod events

✅ Analyzed container logs

✅ Examined previous container logs

✅ Verified resource utilization

✅ Reviewed liveness and readiness probes

✅ Checked application dependencies

✅ Investigated node health

🎯 Root Cause:

The application was consuming more memory than expected and periodically exceeded its configured limits.

Kubernetes terminated the container, causing the pod to restart repeatedly.

Additionally, aggressive liveness probe settings increased restart frequency.

After tuning memory limits and adjusting probe configurations, the pod stabilized.

💡 Key Takeaway:

When troubleshooting Frequent Pod Restarts, focus on identifying the actual trigger behind the restart.

Always verify:

• Application logs

• OOMKilled events

• CPU and Memory utilization

• Liveness probes

• Readiness probes

• Dependency connectivity

• Node health

Useful commands:

kubectl get pods

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous

kubectl top pod

Remember:

📌 Restarts are symptoms, not root causes.

📌 Most frequent restart issues are related to resource limits, application crashes, or probe failures.

📌 The Events section and previous container logs often reveal the real problem.
